column15: I liked the prototypes direct manipulation of data points. The ability to filter by selection of attributes was nice as well, also using sliders for quantitative values was well done. Vizable didn't have a handful of the features. Also the prototype's variety of visualizations, and being able to see multiple Viz's at once made a huge difference. Also having an actual line chart made the prototype much more suitable for analytic tasks.
column16: I disliked the prototypes filtering feedback. A lot of times I wasn't positive how many data cases I had filtered out. Vizable's # of # Records in the bottom right corner is a nice feature. Also when I open the protoypes filter panel it would be nice if it went directly to the features that I had previously filtered out in case I want to undo them. This was a nice feature by Vizable. I disliked Vizable's UI, I felt like they compromised aesthetics for function, often times I wasn't sure what I could or should do next.
column21: I felt that both systems need work in the ease in understanding category. But I gave the slight edge to Visable.

column16: Vzible : the return/next action is great but overall, it's difficult to reset settings and start again to a clean chart. The zoom-in/zoom-out feature for barchart is really weird. I understood it is used to get more insight on sub-column (category->subcategory) but sometimes I got new unwanted columns ...  Prototype : black design :( No horizontal barchart ? No direct access to mean/max/min values

column15: The prototype system's ability to select points by drawing circles around scatter plot points was helpful. Also the ability to have multiple charts on screen at once was a useful feature.   I liked Vizable's filter selection and line chart pinch to zoom.
column16: Both system's did not make use of multi touch abilities on the iPad as much I would have thought. Both seemed like  desktop applications ported to the iPad, however the prototype's touch to select was useful (already stated).
column21: Good study on the topic of learning. Learning multi touch gestures without instruction is tough because it is not clear what other gestures are supported.

column15: Prototype -- multiple coordinated views, linking and brushing. Could browse individual records if necessary. Does not restrict me on how I want to plot  Visable: Choosing filters seemed to be more comprehensive. Looks a littke polished though poor color choices..
column16: Prototype: A little buggy, takes too much time to include or exclude, can probably use a gesture instead.   Visable: I can have a good roast session on this...

column12: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/49.0.2623.87 Safari/537.36
column15: For Prototype, I liked the intuitive interface and flexibility. I was able to quickly learn how to navigate the features, and was able to find a way to answer all the questions in the task.  For Vizable, I liked the icons for switching between the bar chart and line graph.
column16: On Prototype, I wished there were a Home or Menu button to get to the main menu to choose the displayed graphs. On that menu, I wish there were an "X" to delete a currently displayed graph.  On Vizable, I found the the interface both limiting and confusing. For example, I could not change the X-axis on the line graph. Also, many of the data fields were not available under the "Filters". As a result, I could not find a way to answer many of the questions in the task.
column21: I rated Prototype as a more "complex" interface, and meant this in a good way. By complex, it offered more flexibility in the choices of interactions to explore the data. However, the interface was well-organized, and easy to learn and navigate.

column21: I felt that the prototype was more complex in  the sense that it had a lot going on in the screen. And the whole thing with the filter. I like that the menu has been abstracted. I like that data has been spelled out for me in the menus like each of the options, product types etc etc BUT I realized on using the system that I would prefer to not look at so much data all the time and thats where I preferred the Vizable system.  The prototype though felt intuitive because it contained the graphs I had already seen in life. Plus I like the option of being able to customize my screen.  I think I had a few problems with the dropdown. Their design and placement could be improved.

column15: Prototype: Supports detailed table view Supports brushing & linking between views Supports multiple views Supports scatter plot Lassoing interaction was fun and useful. Adding charts and removing them was easy and intuitive, if a user is accustomed to ipad-type gestures. I liked the locations of left-chart, right-filter, bottom-detail panels. It was well-designed and good use of space (by auto-hide).  Vizable:  The annotation over visual objects (e.g., % increase/decrease, max/min) was helpful.
column16: Both: How can I filter by dates? Both systems seem to offer no filter-by-dates on the filtering panel. (I may be wrong due to the time limit). Without tutorial or some kind of guidance, I may miss the existence some functionality. (e.g., I only found out about dragging on axes to highlight toward the end of Prototype tasks)  Prototype: The table view keeps vanishing when I scroll down.  Vizable: Didn't support data item level analysis. I was only able to do aggregated(?) analysis (min, max, avg). Line chart's axis requires a date variable. Learning curve.
column21: Good job Ramik&Meeshu! Best of luck to your submission :)
